Issues.Body:
We have lazy modules loaded dynamically in our application. components in these modules are not referenced by another route level component since those components are dynamically generated after manually lazy loading the module.

after v9, it seems like build optimization process is striping out the components that are not referenced in a template. all our lazy module bundles are not generated without components in them and this is breaking out dynamic loading support. Do we have an option to make sure components are always included in a bundle?

```javascript
//lazy module with component not referenced by another component template
@NgModule({
  imports: [CommonModule],
  declarations: [
    InterestQuestionsComponent
  ],
  entryComponents: [
    InterestQuestionsComponent
  ],
  exports: [
    InterestQuestionsComponent
  ]
})
export class EngageModule {
  static forRoot(): ModuleWithProviders<EngageModule> {
    return {
      ngModule: EngageModule,
      providers: [
        InterestQuestionModel
      ]
    };
  }
}

//route definition
{
    path: 'engage-lazy',
    loadChildren: () => import('./../../lazy-modules/engage/engageModule').then((m) => m.EngageModule)
  }
```

after "ng build", bundle for above route 'engage-lazy' route does not include "InterestQuestionsComponent".

we are using typescript v3.8.0-dev.20200207 since compiler is slow due to below issue. rolled back to 3.7.5 and issue still exists.
https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/34699

# 🚀 Feature request: Add possibility to run resolvers when preloading routes

### Relevant Package
This feature request is for @angular/router


### Description
As many applications nowadays use preloading strategies, it would be nice to implement a way to run the associated resolvers while preloading the routes. Currently, only the assets are downloaded and user still has to wait for data to be loaded while navigating throughout the application.


### Proposal
I think that solution can be as simple as exposing a parameter in `preloadingStrategy.preload` method, which is called in order to preload the route. This parameter could be set to false by default (which would make it a non-breaking change). Also, this would enable custom preloading strategies to be configured in a way that the different pages can determine if the resolvers should, or should not be ran.  In my opinion, it's desirable as some resolvers might depend on changes user does on current page. 

```typescript
export class CustomPreloadingStrategy implements PreloadingStrategy {
  preload(route: Route, load: Function): Observable<any> {
    // ...
    return next(true);

    // or more complex option
    return next({ resolver1: true, resolver2: false });
  }
}
```


### Other alternatives I've considered
- exposing an option while adding a resolver in Route config. It seems like it does not belong there as the user don't need to have any preloading strategy set, so the code will be unused. Also, resolvers don't really deal with preloading the routes, as it's the job of the preloading strategy.
```typescript
const routes: Routes[] = [
  {
    path: 'route',
    resolvers: {
      resolver1: {
        use: SomeResolver,
        preload: true
      }
    }
  }
];
```

